/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 658.0 Tm (Abstract) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 644.0 Tm (Roman harbour structures built from a volcanic-ash concrete have survived two thousand years) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 630.0 Tm (of seawater that would destroy modern equivalents in decades. Examining drilled cores from) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 616.0 Tm (three Mediterranean breakwaters, we identify a self-sealing mechanism in which seawater) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 602.0 Tm (reaction with the lime and ash produces durable minerals within cracks, strengthening the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 588.0 Tm (material over time. We discuss why this behaviour has proven difficult to reproduce and what) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 574.0 Tm (it implies for the design of long-lived marine concrete.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 560.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 542.0 Tm (Introduction) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 528.0 Tm (Modern marine concrete is engineered to resist seawater, and it loses. Chloride attack and) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 514.0 Tm (the corrosion of steel reinforcement limit the service life of harbour structures to a) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 500.0 Tm (handful of decades. Against this record stands the awkward fact that Roman breakwaters built) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 486.0 Tm (without steel and without Portland cement have endured for two millennia in the same hostile) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 472.0 Tm (sea.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 458.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 444.0 Tm (This paper examines cores drilled from three Roman marine structures to understand why.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 430.0 Tm (Rather than merely cataloguing their longevity, we focus on the active mechanism by which) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 416.0 Tm (the material appears to repair itself, a behaviour modern concrete conspicuously lacks.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 402.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 384.0 Tm (Materials and Cores) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 370.0 Tm (The Roman recipe combined lime with a volcanic ash and seawater to produce a mortar that) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 356.0 Tm (bound fragments of rock into a mass. Crucially, the material was not inert once set; it) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 342.0 Tm (continued to react with the seawater percolating through it.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 328.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 314.0 Tm (We recovered cylindrical cores from the submerged portions of three breakwaters and examined) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 300.0 Tm (them by microscopy and mineral analysis, paying particular attention to the material filling) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 286.0 Tm (cracks and voids. The contents of those cracks turned out to tell the central story.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 272.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 254.0 Tm (The Self-Sealing Reaction) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 240.0 Tm (Cracks in the Roman concrete were not empty but filled with interlocking crystals of durable) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 226.0 Tm (minerals that had grown after the structure was built. Seawater entering a crack reacted) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 212.0 Tm (with the lime and volcanic ash to precipitate these minerals, which knit the crack closed) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 198.0 Tm (and were themselves resistant to further seawater attack.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 184.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 170.0 Tm (The result is a material that grows stronger where it is damaged. A crack that in modern) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 156.0 Tm (concrete would admit chloride and accelerate failure instead becomes, in the Roman material,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 142.0 Tm (a site of mineral growth and self-repair. Time and seawater, the agents of decay elsewhere,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 128.0 Tm (are here agents of durability.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 114.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 96.0 Tm (Why It Is Hard to Copy) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 82.0 Tm (The obvious question is why we do not simply build this way today. Part of the answer is) Tj
